annotations:
I played The Sims ’til I was 21
 I had a little life that I always wanted
Petey found comfort in the carefully curated world he had created in The Sims video game.  “Real life” proves more complicated.

I make jokes when I been feelin’ uncomfortable
 Am I alright? I really think I’m in trouble
Like many people, Petey and Miya use humor to mask social anxiety, mental health struggles and confusion about the direction of their lives.

“Hey there, darlin’, did ya get ya a haircut?”
 “I think I cut damn near every last one of them”
A variation on a classic dad joke that goes like this: “Did you get a haircut?!” “No, I got them all cut!”

I walked in, you said, ”Damn, that’s a shaved head
 Did you go to the barber, ask for a Natalie Portman?”
A reference to when Natalie Portman shaved her head for her role as Evey Hammond in the 2005 film V for Vendetta.

description.plain:
In Thingamjig, the opening track of Premonitions (2018), the narrator apologizes to someone she’s harmed. Miya Folick shares the following on diymag.com:

“Maybe you made a grave mistake out of selfishness or ignorance,” she explains. “Maybe you were sheltered from the truth, maybe you couldn’t see the lessons presented to you. Maybe you ignored them deliberately. Imagine, next, that someone hurt you in the same way you hurt others and you were forced to confront the cruelty of your actions. That is ‘Thingamajig’. ‘Thingamajig’ is the deepest apology.”

This opening track announces the themes of guilt, responsibility, conflict, and control that will extend throughout the album. Premonitions, the second track, opens by acknowledging the narrator’s “bad behavior.” Later tracks such as Baby Girl also explore conflicted relationships; in Thingamajig the narrator looks at her own behavior, whereas in Baby Girl, it’s the beloved partner who nonetheless “always fucking drown[s] me out.”

body.plain:
In Thingamjig, the opening track of Premonitions (2018), the narrator apologizes to someone she’s harmed. Miya Folick shares the following on diymag.com:

“Maybe you made a grave mistake out of selfishness or ignorance,” she explains. “Maybe you were sheltered from the truth, maybe you couldn’t see the lessons presented to you. Maybe you ignored them deliberately. Imagine, next, that someone hurt you in the same way you hurt others and you were forced to confront the cruelty of your actions. That is ‘Thingamajig’. ‘Thingamajig’ is the deepest apology.”

This opening track announces the themes of guilt, responsibility, conflict, and control that will extend throughout the album. Premonitions, the second track, opens by acknowledging the narrator’s “bad behavior.” Later tracks such as Baby Girl also explore conflicted relationships; in Thingamajig the narrator looks at her own behavior, whereas in Baby Girl, it’s the beloved partner who nonetheless “always fucking drown[s] me out.”

annotations:
All the hands I’ve made
 Grow in time
 Feel my light
 Your plastic bones are mine

The opening lines are vivid and deeply enigmatic. Hands I’ve made? They grow? And whom is the narrator addressing with the imperative “Feel my light”?  And what does it mean to have plastic bones?  Given what comes next, what Folick calls the “deepest apology,” these lines refer to the injuries she’s caused and the attitude she had to those whom she injured.  Made literal: “all the hurts I’ve caused, they don’t fade; they proliferate, grow, spread like weeds in sunlight.  My light, my life, doesn’t heal; it overwhelms and poisons.  And do so because I treat people like putty, bend them to my will, seize them and hold them.”
